":"1234–Overleden","1127–1208":"1127–1208","1183–1277":"1183–1277","Cir 1206":"1206","aproximadamente 1226":"circa 1226","ABT 1228":"circa 1228","1183":"1183","1260":"1260","1239":"1239","1206":"1206","1205":"1205","1127":"1127","1226":"1226","1203":"1203","11 de noviembre de 1208":"11 november 1208","1234":"1234","1256":"1256","1277":"1277","1208":"1208","1207":"1207","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, España":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spanje","Toledo, New Castile, Spain":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spanje","España":"Spanje","Spain":"Spanje"},"en":{"Cir 1206–1239":"1206–1239","1205–Female":"1205–Deceased","1205–Male":"1205–Deceased","1206–1239":"1206–1239","1207–Female":"1207–Deceased","1203–1256":"1203–1256","1226–1260":"1226–1260","1234–Male":"1234–Deceased","1127–1208":"1127–1208","1183–1277":"1183–1277","Cir 1206":"1206","aproximadamente 1226":"about 1226","ABT 1228":"about 1228","1183":"1183","1260":"1260","1239":"1239","1206":"1206","1205":"1205","1127":"1127","1226":"1226","1203":"1203","11 de noviembre de 1208":"11 November 1208","1234":"1234","1256":"1256","1277":"1277","1208":"1208","1207":"1207","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, España":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain","Toledo, New Castile, Spain":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain","España":"Spain","Spain":"Spain","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Estevanes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Hispanic (Mexico; <b>Estévane</b>): variant of <b>Estévanez</b>, a patronymic from the personal name   Estevan  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Estevan","meanings":["Spanish: from a variant of the personal name   Esteban  ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Toledo","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Luis, Jorge, Manuel, Ramon, Rafael, Juan, Antonio, Jesus, Miguel, Roberto, Carlos, Francisco.","Spanish and Jewish (Sephardic): habitational name from the city in central Spain, which was the capital of the Visigothic state between the 6th and 8th centuries. Its role declined for three centuries after the Muslim invasion of Spain, until it was taken as the capital of the kingdom of Castile between the 11th and 16th centuries. It was a major cultural and political center throughout the Middle Ages, and was also the home of an important Jewish community. The placename, first recorded in Latin as <i>Toletum</i>, is of obscure etymology, possibly connected with <i>Toleto</i> in Piedmont; Jewish tradition connects it with Hebrew <i>toledot</i> ‘generations’, but this is no more than folk etymology. Compare   Toledano  .","Jewish (Sephardic): also an adoption of the Spanish surname (see 1 above) at the moment of conversion to Roman Catholicism. After the return to Judaism (generations later), some descendants retained the surname their families used as Catholics."],"variants":[{"name":"Toledano","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Shlomo, Igal, Moshe, Shimon, Ehud, Shmuel, Yehuda.  Spanish Alberto, Gonzalo, Alina, Carlos, Conrado, Elena, Enrique, Evelia, Luis, Manuel, Miguel, Ramona.  French Gabrielle, Michel.","Spanish and Jewish (Sephardic): habitational name for someone from Toledo (see   Toledo  ), from an adjectival form of the placename."]}]},{"name":"Luna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Norse <i>Rúna</i>, a short form of various female compound names formed with <i>rún</i> ‘rune, secret lore’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Doña Luna Estevanes de Toledo was born in 1206, in Diócesis de Toledo, Spain, her father, Esteban Illán de San Román Bermey de Toledo, was 80 and her mother, Elisabeth Luna   Estevanez, was 23. She married Fernán Pérez  Suárez de Toledo about 1228, in Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1239, in Spain, at the age of 33."},"et":{"Cir 1206–1239":"1206–1239","1205–Female":"1205–Surnud","1205–Male":"1205–Surnud","1206–1239":"1206–1239","1207–Female":"1207–Surnud","1203–1256":"1203–1256","1226–1260":"1226–1260","1234–Male":"1234–Surnud","1127–1208":"1127–1208","1183–1277":"1183–1277","Cir 1206":"1206","aproximadamente 1226":"umbes 1226","ABT 1228":"umbes 1228","1183":"1183","1260":"1260","1239":"1239","1206":"1206","1205":"1205","1127":"1127","1226":"1226","1203":"1203","11 de noviembre de 1208":"11. november 1208","1234":"1234","1256":"1256","1277":"1277","1208":"1208","1207":"1207","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, España":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Hispaania","Toledo, New Castile, Spain":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Hispaania","España":"Hispaania","Spain":"Hispaania"},"fi":{"Cir 1206–1239":"1206–1239","1205–Female":"1205–Kuollut","1205–Male":"1205–Kuollut","1206–1239":"1206–1239","1207–Female":"1207–Kuollut","1203–1256":"1203–1256","1226–1260":"1226–1260","1234–Male":"1234–Kuollut","1127–1208":"1127–1208","1183–1277":"1183–1277","Cir 1206":"1206","aproximadamente 1226":"noin 1226","ABT 1228":"noin 1228","1183":"1183","1260":"1260","1239":"1239","1206":"1206","1205":"1205","1127":"1127","1226":"1226","1203":"1203","11 de noviembre de 1208":"11. marraskuuta 1208","1234":"1234","1256":"1256","1277":"1277","1208":"1208","1207":"12